x4freetext: 150 kV-cascade accelerator with pulsed ion source
T(d,n)alpha reaction on t-Ti targets with copper
backing. 2 ns neutron pulses were produced every 200 ns
more than 10**9 neutrons/sec in 4 pi were obtained.
The sample was of natural isotopic composition and
consisted of an hollow cylinder (external diameter=70mm
internal diameter=0 to 50mm, height=70mm). The internal
diameter was determined such that the average path of
neutrons in the sample was about 1/4 to 1/2 of the
Time of flight with pulsed neutron source.
The flight-path was about 2 meters and the overall
time resolution, including geometrical effects, was of
Alpha particles from the d-t reaction were used
for absolute determination of the neutron source
diameter = 38 mm) associated with a photomultiplier-
operated in space charge mode at the last dynode for
better neutron-gamma discrimination- was used to
A surface barrier silicon detector was used
for the detection of alpha particles.
Two other neutron detectors (a BF3 counter and a
scintillation detector) were used to control the
Time of flight spectra were converted to energy spectra
by a computer program performing also all the below
The neutron source strength was absolutely determined
by the associated particle method. Influence of the
The obtained spectra were corrected for =
(calculated by the Monte-Carlo method as well as by
.Absorption and multiple scattering in the sample
(calculated by the Monte-Carlo method as well as by
Data are given with their statistical err. only
The absolute statistical error on the content of the

-n(I) and O(I) are the content of the I-Th channel,
respectively with and without sample in the neutron
-mw and mwo are the monitor`s counting rates
corresponding to the spectra measured respectively
with and without sample in the neutron beam.
In addition to the given statistical error,
there is a 10% systematic error which consists of:
-the error on the absolute source strength (4%)
